The "ape car" to avoid collisions
In the context of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, for example, takes the flight of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers of the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Centre have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Centre for Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Two, Director-General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and the Development of Brand Management, BR23C constitutes an extension of the Safety Shield of four areas produced by Nissan.
This robot is designed to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the vehicles of the manufacturer's house.
During the flight, each water creates its own oval-shaped personal space which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing is the bees' compound eyes, able to see in all directions with an angle above 300 degrees, and that allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual feature, engineers have developed what they have defined as a localization laser(Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately allows you to prevent the collision.
"At the moment that it detects an obstacle, the small robot imitates the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction turning on the wheels at right angle or greater to avoid the collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is completely instinctive.
"If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and engineer head of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot turn upwards or downwards, or even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which they can rotate its wheels and not exploit infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and to act from this data.
It does not require the storage of information or intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruptions and with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, nor about mega."
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan hopes will be serial in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of units with a GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to destination by avoiding obstacles in the path.
